{"parse":{"title":"Alltagsgeschichte","pageid":3184347,"revid":765659445,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Alltagsgeschichte</b></i> is a form of <a href=\"/wiki/Microhistory\" title=\"Microhistory\">microhistory</a> that was particularly prevalent amongst German historians during the 1980s. It was founded by historians <a href=\"/wiki/Alf_Luedtke\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Alf Luedtke\">Alf Luedtke</a> and <a href=\"https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hans_Medick\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"de:Hans Medick\">Hans Medick</a>.\n</p><p>The name comes from German, where <i>Alltag</i> means \"everyday life\"; it can thus be roughly translated as \"everyday history\". In this sense, <i>Alltagsgeschichte</i> can be considered part of the wider Marxian historical school of '<a href=\"/wiki/People%27s_history\" title=\"People&#39;s history\">history from below</a>'. \n</p><p>The purpose of <i>Alltagsgeschichte</i> is to find and prove the links between the down-to-earth, everyday, basic experiences of ordinary people in a society, and the broad social and political changes which occur in that society. Because this is such a massively broad endeavour to undertake, it can only feasibly be practised on the most minute of scales. Thus <i>Alltagsgeschichte</i> becomes a form of microhistory.\n</p><p>Its leading exponents include <a href=\"/wiki/Paul_Veyne\" title=\"Paul Veyne\">Paul Veyne</a> and Michel Rouche in France, and Peter Carr in the United Kingdom. <i>Alltagsgeschichte</i> can also be linked to the Italian historical doctrine of <i>Microstoria</i> (microhistory).\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Publications\">Publications</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Alltagsgeschichte&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Publications\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>The History of Everyday Life</i> by German historian Alf L\u00fcdtke</li>\n<li><i>Alltagsgeschichte - ein Bericht von unterwegs</i>, by Alf L\u00fcdtke, in <i>Historische Anthropologie No. 11</i> (2003), pp. 278-295</li>\n<li><i>A History of Private Life: from Pagan Rome to Byzantium</i>, Paul Veyne, ed. (Editions du Seuil, 1985)</li>\n<li><i>Portavo: an Irish Townland and its Peoples</i>, Parts One and Two, by Peter Carr (White Row, 2003 and 2005)</li>\n<li><i>The History of Everyday Life: A second chapter\", by Paul Steege, Andrew Bergerson, Maureen Healy and Pamela E. Swett, in </i>The Journal of Modern History<i>, No. 80 (June 2008), pp. 358-378</i></li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Hourglass.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Hourglass.svg/20px-Hourglass.svg.png\" width=\"20\" height=\"33\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Hourglass.svg/30px-Hourglass.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/Hourglass.svg/40px-Hourglass.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"189\" data-file-height=\"315\" /></a></td><td><i>This history article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Alltagsgeschichte&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Hist-stub\" title=\"Template:Hist-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template_talk:Hist-stub\" title=\"Template talk:Hist-stub\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Hist-stub&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit